      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix: clean up Kiro CLI helper processes",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- launch Kiro CLI commands with a dedicated process group established before `exec`\n- terminate residual helpers after normal parent exit, escalating from `TERM` to `KILL` before draining inherited pipes\n- preserve child standard streams when the host starts with a standard descriptor closed\n- preserve existing timeout, cancellation, output, and exit-status behavior\n- strengthen the inherited-pipe regression to require cleanup of a helper that ignores graceful termination\n\nFollow-up to #1533 and #1535.\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe merged fix bounded pipe draining, but its best-effort `setpgid` call happened after `Foundation.Process.run()`. On macOS the child can cross `exec` before that call, causing `setpgid` to fail with `EACCES`. A normally exiting Kiro parent could therefore return while a pipe-holding helper survived outside any controllable process group.\n\nThis change uses `posix_spawn` with `POSIX_SPAWN_SETPGROUP`, matching the repository's existing pre-exec process-group pattern.\n\n## Proof\n\nExact head: `1d7236a93aa98f6f8ff768ff15160eecad2b4a13`\n\n- focused Kiro and process-group tests: 33 passed\n- closed-stdout launcher regression: passed with the test runner's stdout descriptor unavailable\n- `make test`: 470 deterministic selections across 40 shards passed\n- `make check`: parser/package/release guards passed; SwiftFormat clean; SwiftLint 0 violations\n- `swift build -c release --product CodexBarCLI`: passed\n- release CLI synthetic Kiro proof: parent exited normally, descendant retained the output pipe and ignored `HUP`/`TERM`, command returned successfully in 0.80s, descendant was terminated\n- local autoreview: no accepted or actionable findings\n- Public Model Identifier Gate: PASS; no model identifiers added to source, tests, artifacts, logs, or public proof\n\nThe runtime proof used an isolated temporary home and synthetic account data. No live credentials, browser data, Keychain access, private payloads, or user-identifying paths were used.\n\n## Risk\n\nThe new process launcher is package-internal and currently used only by Kiro. macOS process-group and closed-standard-descriptor behavior is covered locally; CI validates the conditional Linux build.\n",
